        ('Common Website Security Vulnerabilities', '<ul><li><strong>Outdated CMS/plugins:</strong> 56% of WordPress hacks exploit outdated plugins</li><li><strong>Weak passwords:</strong> "admin/admin" is still the most common CMS login</li><li><strong>No SSL certificate:</strong> Google marks HTTP sites as "Not Secure" — destroying trust instantly</li><li><strong>SQL injection:</strong> Unprotected forms can expose your entire database</li><li><strong>No backup strategy:</strong> If ransomware hits and you have no backup, you\'re starting from zero</li></ul>'),
        ('Essential Security Practices for Every Business Website', '<ol><li><strong>SSL certificate:</strong> HTTPS is mandatory. Free options available via Let\'s Encrypt</li><li><strong>Regular updates:</strong> Update CMS, plugins, and themes within 48 hours of security patches</li><li><strong>Strong passwords:</strong> Minimum 12 characters, unique for each account, use a password manager</li><li><strong>Automated backups:</strong> Daily backups stored in a separate location (cloud storage, not the same server)</li><li><strong>Web Application Firewall (WAF):</strong> Cloudflare or Sucuri blocks common attacks before they reach your server</li><li><strong>Two-factor authentication:</strong> Add 2FA to all admin accounts</li><li><strong>Regular security audits:</strong> Monthly vulnerability scans and annual penetration testing</li></ol>'),
